<h3 id="macos">MacOS</h3>

<ol>
  <li>plug your ESP32 into your Laptopâ€™s USB port</li>
  <li>(in the Finder) Navigate to Applications &gt; Utilities</li>
  <li>find the Terminal, open it</li>
  <li>in the Terminal type the following: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">screen /dev/tty.</code></li>
  <li>hit the TAB key, one of the results should be <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">tty.SLAB_USBtoUART</code></li>
  <li>add an <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">SL</code> to the command above so it reads: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">screen /dev/tty.SL</code></li>
  <li>hit the TAB key again, autocomplete should give you: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">screen /dev/tty.SLAB_USBtoUART</code></li>
  <li>add the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">BAUD</code> rate (<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">115200</code>) to the end of the command above: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">screen /dev/tty.SLAB_USBtoUART 115200</code></li>
  <li>hit ENTER once to execute the command</li>
  <li>hit ENTER a second time at the gray screen, which should bring up the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">command prompt</code>: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&gt;&gt;&gt;</code></li>
</ol>

<h3 id="windows-10">Windows 10</h3>

<ol>
  <li>plug your <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">ESP32</code> into your Laptopâ€™s USB port</li>
  <li>check the list of identified <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">COM</code> ports in the Windows Device Manager
    <ul>
      <li>we need the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">COM</code> number for the device labeled <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Silicon Labs CP210x USB to UART Bridge (COM3)</code>, write this number down for use later</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>(in the Start Menu) Navigate to Putty</li>
  <li>(in Putty) select Serial and set:
    <ul>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Serial line to connect to</code>: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">COM3</code> (use the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">COM</code> number from step 2)</li>
      <li><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Speed (baud)</code>: to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">115200</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>click <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Open</code></li>
  <li>hit ENTER once to bring up the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">command prompt</code>: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&gt;&gt;&gt;</code></li>
</ol>
